            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "of a fever and of a bloody flixe",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "R. V.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " “of fever and dysentery”]. The words are technical such as a physician, as St Luke is reputed to have been, would be likely to use in describing the disease. The first, which is in the plural number, implies the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fits of fever",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " which occur at intervals in such diseases as ague.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
