        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "It",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "was so",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "it came to pass",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fever",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a fever",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "dysentery",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of a bloody flux",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "unto",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "laying",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "healed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and laid",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc., and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "healed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The father of Publius",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The fact of the father of Publius being alive and living in Malta is a further indication that the term ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὁ πρῶτος τῆς νήσου ισ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " an official title. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Lay sick",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Συνέχεσθαι ισ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " also the usual medical expression for being ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "taken sick",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of any disease (see the numerous passages quoted by Hobart, pp. 3, 4, from Galen and Hippocrates). It is used by St. Luke, with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πυρετῴ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and in the same sense in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 4:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Lay.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Κατακεῖσθαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is used especially of lying in bed from sickness (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 1:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 5:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 9:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It answers to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "decumbo",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in Latin. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Sick of fever and dysentery",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πυρετοῖς καὶ δυσεντερία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "συνεχόμενον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The terms here used are all professional ones. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Πυρετός",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the plural, is of frequent occurrence in Hippocrates, Aretaeus, and Galen, but elsewhere in the New Testament always in the singular; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δυσεντερία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", only found here in the New Testament, is the regular technical word for a \"dysentery,\" and is frequently in medical writers coupled with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πυρετοί",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πυρετός",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as indicating different stages of the same illness. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Laying his hands on him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". So ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 16:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"They shall lay hands on the sick, and they shall recover\" (see also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 9:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 19:13, 15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 5:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 7:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 8:23, 25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 13:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 9:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is also spoken of as an accompaniment of prayer in confirmation, ordination, etc. It has been remarked as curious that the two actions of taking up serpents and healing the sick by the laying on of hands should be in such close juxtaposition both here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 16:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It suggests the thought whether Luke had seen the passage in St. Mark; or whether the writer of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 16:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " had seen ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 28:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Or is the coincidence accidental, arising out of the facts? Acts 28:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Sick (συνεχόμενον)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., taken or holden. See on taken, Luke 4:38.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Lit., taken or holden. See on taken, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 4:38",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Fever (πυρετοῖς)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., fevers. This peculiarly medical use of the plural is confined to Luke in the New Testament. It denotes successive and varying attacks of fever.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Bloody flux (δυσεντερίᾳ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Only here in New Testament. Our word dysentery is nearly a transcript of it. Hippocrates often speaks of the two complaints in combination.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Healed (ἰάσατο)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "See on Luke 6:19. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "See on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 6:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
